metry. We show theoretical arguments that the quest of inversion can be relaxed and other types of defect quantum emitters are in contention, such as V1 center in 4H $\mathrm{SiC}$. In particular, $4 \mathrm{H} \mathrm{SiC}$ hosts spin-active emitters, e.g., a recent study on molybdenum ${ }^{48,49}$, that might have also favorable optical stability against stray electric fields. Quantum emitters in other semiconductors such as $\mathrm{ZnO}^{50,51}$ and $\mathrm{GaN}^{52,53}$ should be also revisited in this regard. Our study also provides a guidance to design novel defect quantum emitters in $2 \mathrm{D}$ compound materials ${ }^{54-58}$ for stable spin-to-photon interface at a single photon level.

